@krua yeah you can! Changing to raw distros is a learning experience. Your sound won't work, your network would keep on disconnecting.

Mint is based on Ubuntu, Ubuntu is based on Debian. When you switch to using Debian, you are working with a raw lightweight thing that comes with no baggage - you have to customize it to do your bidding. And that will teach you about more about Linux itself.

Arch is even hardcore. They have a do-it-yourself principle. You would learn even more!

@coymeetsworld yeah. A lot of beginners get turned off by the terminal, and start memorizing the commands. I have seen people at workplace writing large evernote docs to store large commands. Like which command to invoke to run linting, which to run the tests etc.

If you change the order of flags, they would tell you that your command is wrong!

My vision for this is a comprehensive article that makes learning and using commands fun - without having to memorizing it. Maybe more familiarity with manpages and help options.

